// ---- TEAMS (10) — replace name/fullName/base/principal/chassis/powerUnit with real data ----
// owner:       Team Owner / CEO shown on the team profile
// wdc / wcc:   World Drivers' / Constructors' Championships won — shown as stat boxes on the team profile
// description: short "about" blurb shown on the team profile
const TEAMS = [
  {id:1,  name:"Kinghorn",      fullName:"Kinghorn Formula One Racing Team",          color:"#0c4b28", base:"Woking, United Kingdom",  principal:"George Tills",         chassis:"KH-26", powerUnit:"Kinghorn",            firstEntry:1973,
    owner:"Marty Barron", wdc:6, wcc:11,
    description:"Kinghorn has stood among the great names of British automobile manufacturing since the 1940s, building a reputation for high-performance engineering that has carried the marque to prominence both in England and across the world. That same pursuit of excellence led the team into Formula One in 1973, where it wasted little time establishing itself among the sport's elite. Racing under the unmistakable British Racing Green, Kinghorn's cars have become one of the most recognisable sights on the grid, frequently found at the front of the field and leading from pole position. Over the decades, Kinghorn has developed and championed some of the sport's greatest talents, producing multiple World Champions along the way. The team has long favoured continuity over turnover, building lasting relationships with drivers once they've proven themselves and earning a reputation for loyalty that is rare in modern motorsport. This philosophy has fostered a close-knit, family-like atmosphere within the team, and it shows: former drivers and champions consistently speak with fondness and gratitude about their years at Kinghorn. That legacy of success continues to be written today, with the team's cars and colours remaining a fixture at the sharp end of the Constructors' Championship. Kinghorn's driver lineup blends experience with fresh talent, a balance the team has long relied upon to sustain its competitiveness while nurturing the next generation of champions. Above all, Kinghorn's story is defined by consistency: decades of engineering pedigree, a distinctive identity on track, and a culture built on loyalty and belonging that has made it one of Formula One's most respected and enduring teams."},
  {id:2,  name:"Cavalla Nera",  fullName:"Scuderia Cavalla Nera",                     color:"#424242", base:"Turin, Italy",           principal:"Flávio Sartini",       chassis:"CN68", powerUnit:"Cavalla Nera",        firstEntry:1958,
    owner:"Ermes Bencivenni", wdc:9, wcc:19,
    description:"Since 1958, Scuderia Cavalla Nera has been one of Formula One's defining presences, an Italian institution built on a legacy of sports and supercar excellence. Known simply as 'the black mares', the team's sleek black liveries with silver highlights have become one of the most iconic sights in motorsport, embodying more than six decades of speed, style, and prestige. Cavalla Nera's cars carry a reputation as demanding as they are dominant: blisteringly fast, but notoriously difficult to master. Taming a Cavalla Nera is considered one of the great tests in Formula One, and only a select group of drivers throughout the team's history have managed to unlock true synergy with the car. The team is known for giving rookies their chance behind the wheel, but few earn a lasting place in the garage — those who do, like Alexander Everill and Callum Sykes, are remembered as drivers who truly understood the mare. This exacting standard is central to the team's identity. Where other outfits build around comfort and consistency, Cavalla Nera has built its legend on the raw challenge of its machinery, producing multiple World Constructors' and World Drivers' Championships from a philosophy that rewards only the boldest and most adaptable talent. It is a team that asks everything of its drivers, and immortalises the ones who deliver. Guided today by Team Owner Ermes Bencivenni and Team Principal Flávio Sartini, Scuderia Cavalla Nera remains one of Formula One's most storied and respected teams — a benchmark of Italian engineering pedigree and an ever-present force at the front of the grid."},
  {id:3,  name:"Refresh",       fullName:"Refresh F1 Racing",                         color:"#37ddb4", base:"Silverstone, United Kingdom",  principal:"Anton Lafrentz",       chassis:"REF26", powerUnit:"Refresh Powertrains", firstEntry:2000,
    owner:"Isaac Fisher", wdc:4, wcc:4,
    description:"When Refresh F1 Racing arrived on the grid in 2000, it marked a turning point for the sport. As the first energy drink brand to enter Formula One, the team brought with it a bold, modern identity that stood in sharp contrast to the traditional manufacturers and racing houses that had long defined the paddock. Early skepticism about a newcomer with no motorsport pedigree quickly gave way to respect, as Refresh proved it belonged among the sport's elite. The team's breakthrough came in the mid-2000s, crowning Kieran William World Champion in back-to-back seasons before claiming a hat-trick of Constructors' Championships — a run that firmly established Refresh Powertrains as a serious force in Formula One engineering. That early success set the tone for a team unafraid to challenge convention and built for the long game, blending youthful energy with increasingly serious technical ambition. Refresh has never shied away from developing its own talent, giving young drivers genuine opportunities to grow within the team rather than seeking the finished product elsewhere. That patience and faith in its driver pairings has become something of a team hallmark, weathering leaner years in pursuit of long-term chemistry on the pit wall and in the garage. It's an approach that eventually paid off again with Leon Radvan, who returned the team to the top step of the championship and delivered back-to-back title-winning seasons. Under the leadership of Team Owner Isaac Fisher and Team Principal Anton Lafrentz, Refresh F1 Racing continues to carry the identity that first set it apart on the grid: sharp, modern, and relentlessly ambitious. More than two decades since disrupting the establishment, Refresh remains one of the sport's most dynamic and closely watched teams, with four Constructors' and four Drivers' Championships to its name."},
  {id:4,  name:"MerQury",       fullName:"MerQury Racing",                   color:"#ffbb00", base:"Coventry, United Kingdom",  principal:"Joachim Schlösser",    chassis:"Q09-26", powerUnit:"Kinghorn",            firstEntry:2009,
    resultsName:"Kinghorn MerQury",
    owner:"David Rigby", wdc:1, wcc:1,
    description:"MerQury Racing brings a distinctly technological identity to Formula One. Beyond the track, the British company is known for developing the smart systems and connected technology found in road cars around the world, and that engineering DNA has shaped the team's approach to racing since it joined the grid in 2009, stepping in after the departure of Portugal's Atlantica. The team's arrival made an immediate impression. Within its first four seasons, MerQury established itself as a genuine title contender, producing a World Champion and following it with a Constructors' Championship the very next year — a rapid rise that few debutant teams have matched. The years that followed saw the team built around proven, experienced talent, with a driver line-up capable of consistently strong results, even as the wider competitive landscape shifted around them. Like many teams, MerQury has moved through cycles of dominance and rebuilding, and the 2022 regulation changes brought renewed momentum, with the team steadily closing the gap back toward the front of the grid. Central to MerQury's philosophy has been a belief in developing talent and standing by its drivers through both strong and difficult stretches, a loyalty that has come to define the team's character in the paddock as much as its technical ambition. Powered by Kinghorn engines and led by Team Owner David Rigby and Team Principal Joachim Schlösser, MerQury Racing continues to work toward recapturing the form of its early years. With one Constructors' and one Drivers' Championship already part of its history, the team remains focused on the engineering precision and steady development that first brought it to the top of the sport."},
  {id:5,  name:"Frecciata",     fullName:"Scuderia Frecciata Di Altera", color:"#78d366", base:"Bolognia, Italy",           principal:"Rico Sessa",           chassis:"CVF-2026", powerUnit:"Cavalla Nera",        firstEntry:2021,
    resultsName:"Frecciata Cavalla Nera",
    owner:"Luigi Altera", wdc:0, wcc:0,
    description:"Scuderia Frecciata Di Altera occupies a grid slot with a rich and layered history. Long home to the Swiss precision of Lynx and later reborn as Cavalla Nera's junior outfit VentoGrigio, the entry found its current identity in 2021, when Italian businessman and lifelong motorsport enthusiast Luigi Altera acquired the team from Cavalla Nera. Under new ownership and a fresh livery, the team was reborn as Scuderia Frecciata Di Altera, carrying forward its predecessor's technical foundation while charting an independent course. The team's early seasons were shaped by an ambitious driver pairing, retaining rising talent from its junior team days alongside experienced championship-winning firepower. That period brought valuable lessons in team-building, as Frecciata worked to establish its own culture and identity separate from its former parent squad. The appointment of Rico Sessa as Team Principal marked a turning point, ushering in a period of sharpened focus and steady on-track improvement. Racing in green, red and white with power units supplied by the other Italian team on the grid, Frecciata has built its reputation on ambition and improvement, climbing the order year after year as its management and driver line-up have matured together. The team has also earned a name for giving drivers a fresh platform to rebuild and rediscover form, a role it continues to embrace as it develops its roster for the seasons ahead. Led by Team Owner Luigi Altera and Team Principal Rico Sessa, Scuderia Frecciata Di Altera remains one of the grid's most determined outfits — a team still writing its own chapter in Formula One, with its sights firmly set on competing among the sport's very best."},
  {id:6,  name:"Faucon",        fullName:"Equipe Faucon Moteurs",                     color:"#68a5df", base:"Lyon, France",          principal:"Jean-Pierre Fortier",  chassis:"F6-26", powerUnit:"Faucon Moteurs",      firstEntry:1995,
    owner:"Salomon Gaillard", wdc:2, wcc:2,
    description:"Equipe Faucon Moteurs has been part of the fabric of Formula One since 1995, one of a small number of manufacturers on the grid to design, build, and race with power units of its own creation. As a French automaker with deep engineering roots, Faucon brought technical independence to the sport from day one, a philosophy of self-reliance that continues to define the team nearly three decades later. Faucon's history has had its share of high points, including Constructors' and Drivers' Championship success in the late 2000s that remain a proud reference point for the team. In the years since, Faucon has settled into the role of a resilient, consistent midfield presence, a team that has weathered shifting regulations and fierce competition from wealthier rivals while continuing to field its own engines season after season, a feat fewer and fewer constructors can claim. Central to Faucon's identity is its independence and its loyalty to its own engineering programme, even through periods when that commitment has come at a cost on raceday. The team has remained fully backed by its parent company and long-standing sponsors, a foundation of stability that has allowed it to keep investing in development rather than chase short-term fixes. That patience, paired with a driver line-up bringing genuine championship-level experience, underpins the team's belief that a return toward the front of the grid is within reach. Led by Team Owner Salomon Gaillard and Team Principal Jean-Pierre Fortier, Equipe Faucon Moteurs remains one of Formula One's most self-sufficient outfits — a French institution built on independence, perseverance, and two Championship titles that continue to fuel its ambitions for the future."},
  {id:7,  name:"ACXS",          fullName:"ACXS Davis Motorsports",       color:"#d41717", base:"Austin, USA",                  principal:"Bernardo Miranda",     chassis:"7-AXCS", powerUnit:"Cavalla Nera",        firstEntry:2018,
    resultsName:"ACXS Cavalla Nera",
    owner:"Anthony Davis", wdc:0, wcc:0,
    description:"ACXS Davis Motorsports brought a bold slice of American motorsport culture to Formula One when it joined the grid in 2019, taking over the entry once held by Xtreme. Instantly recognisable in its red, white, and blue livery, the team represents the Formula One arm of a wider motorsport operation built by businessman Anthony Davis, whose organisation has spent years establishing itself as a serious competitor in disciplines like MotoGP and NASCAR before setting its sights on Formula One. Though still a young outfit by the sport's standards, ACXS has approached its entry with the long-term ambition and resources of a team built for sustained competition rather than a short-lived venture. Davis has been open about the team's growth mindset, treating its early seasons as a foundation-building period focused on infrastructure, driver development, and steadily closing the gap to the sport's established midfield. That ambition is matched by ownership with proven pedigree in high-level motorsport, and a belief that the same competitive spirit driving ACXS's success in other categories can translate to Formula One. The team has made a point of giving opportunity to talent capable of growing alongside the project, part of a broader strategy aimed at building a driver line-up that can carry ACXS toward the front of the grid in the years to come. Powered by Cavalla Nera engines and led by Team Owner Anthony Davis and Team Principal Bernardo Miranda, ACXS Davis Motorsports remains one of the grid's most ambitious young teams — determined to establish American motorsport at the very top of Formula One once again."},
  {id:8,  name:"Equin",         fullName:"Equin GP Racing Team",             color:"#6d0f59", base:"Sunderland, United Kingdom",  principal:"Cecil Glynn",          chassis:"CE98-26", powerUnit:"Kinghorn",            firstEntry:1998,
    resultsName:"Kinghorn Equin",
    owner:"Boyd Southgate", wdc:0, wcc:0,
    description:"Equin GP Racing Team has been a fixture on the Formula One grid since 1998, one of the sport's true independent constructors and a team whose longevity speaks to a quiet resilience rarely celebrated in a sport defined by championships and podiums. While silverware has so far eluded the team, Equin has built a reputation as a dependable, hard-working presence in the midfield, consistently fielding competitive cars season after season. Rather than chasing headlines, Equin has focused on steady development and the long-term growth of its people, both on the pit wall and behind the wheel. The team has become known for giving emerging talent a genuine platform to prove themselves in Formula One, often taking a patient, developmental approach to driver line-ups that prioritises long-term potential over short-term results. That philosophy continues to shape the team today, with a driver pairing that blends fresh energy and promise, reflecting Equin's ongoing commitment to nurturing the next generation of Formula One talent. The team's engineers and strategists have likewise earned respect in the paddock for extracting consistent performance from limited resources, a hallmark of the team's identity since its earliest years on the grid. Powered by Kinghorn engines and led by Team Owner Boyd Southgate and Team Principal Cecil Glynn, Equin GP Racing Team remains a determined and enduring presence in Formula One — a team built on patience, development, and the belief that its breakthrough season is still ahead of it."},
  {id:9,  name:"Atlas",         fullName:"Atlas Petrol F1",                    color:"#223897", base:"Ghent, Belgium",         principal:"Arturo Accorsi",       chassis:"AP37", powerUnit:"Faucon Moteurs",      firstEntry:2015,
    resultsName:"Atlas Petrol Faucon",
    owner:"Allain Monet", wdc:1, wcc:1,
    description:"Atlas Petrol F1 has been part of Formula One since 1989, giving the Belgian team one of the longest continuous histories on the grid. Instantly recognisable by its white and dark blue livery, styled after the latitude and longitude lines of its globe logo, Atlas has carried Belgian motorsport identity through more than three decades of the sport's evolution. The team's history includes a notable chapter of collaboration, competing for over a decade alongside Swedish manufacturer Astraea Automobiles after the two joined forces in 2002. That partnership helped sustain the team through a competitive era before the two returned to independent paths in 2014, with Atlas continuing on under its original name and identity. Throughout the 2000s and into the 2010s, Atlas established itself as a strong and respected presence in the midfield, built on the Constructors' and Drivers' Championship success the team achieved in its earliest, breakthrough years. Atlas has always prided itself on resourcefulness, extracting strong results from a compact operation and building a reputation for punching above its weight against larger, better-funded rivals. That resilience has been tested in more recent seasons, as sweeping regulation changes reshaped the competitive order across the sport, but the team's engineers and leadership remain focused on rediscovering the pace and reliability that once made Atlas a fixture near the front of the midfield. Led by Team Owner Allain Monet and Team Principal Arturo Accorsi, Atlas Petrol F1 continues to draw on more than 30 years of Formula One heritage, with a single Constructors' and Drivers' Championship anchoring a legacy the team is determined to build upon once again."},
  {id:10, name:"Leonides",      fullName:"Leonides Formula One",               color:"#7e45ac", base:"Mannheim, Germany",        principal:"Markus Schuster",      chassis:"Leo-0-26", powerUnit:"Faucon Moteurs",     firstEntry:2011,
    resultsName:"Leonides Faucon",
    owner:"Sascha Krumm", wdc:0, wcc:0,
    description:"Leonides Formula One joined the grid in 2011, stepping into the space left behind by Inara's departure and bringing German engineering ambition to the sport as a Faucon-powered constructor. Founded as a passion project by Sascha Krumm, son of Leonides AG chairman Gerhardt Krumm, the team represents a unique presence on the grid: a Formula One outfit born from genuine motorsport enthusiasm within a larger industrial parent company. In the years since its debut, Leonides has faced the persistent challenge familiar to many independent outfits on the grid — competing against better-resourced rivals with a fraction of the budget. The team has been open about the difficulties of balancing its Formula One ambitions against the wider financial priorities of its parent company, a tension that has shaped much of its story and pushed the team to find efficiency and resourcefulness wherever it can. Despite these constraints, Leonides has remained a fixture in the sport, valued for its willingness to give young drivers a genuine opportunity to develop at the highest level. The team has increasingly leaned into youth development as a core part of its long-term strategy, seeing driver development as one of the most valuable tools available to a team working within tighter financial limits. Led by Team Owner Sascha Krumm and Team Principal Markus Schuster, Leonides Formula One continues to compete with a spirit shaped by grit and determination rather than budget size, one of the grid's most persistent underdog stories and a team that keeps building toward the breakthrough it believes is still to come."},
];

